      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After Mary Matalin's "sniveling hypocrite" press release attack on Gov. Bill Clinton and her half-hearted apology embarrassed the Bush campaign, you quoted an unnamed Republican senator wistfully remembering Lee Atwater, the President's negative campaign tactician in 1988 (news article, Aug. 4). "Lee didn't have to issue any apologies," he said.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>After Mary Matalin's "sniveling hypocrite" press release attack on Gov. Bill Clinton and her half-hearted apology embarrassed the Bush campaign, you quoted an unnamed Republican senator wistfully remembering Lee Atwater, the President's negative campaign tactician in 1988 (news article, Aug. 4). "Lee didn't have to issue any apologies," he said.</p>
        <p>If memory serves, Mr. Atwater, dying of cancer, publicly apologized to Michael S. Dukakis for the campaign attacks, and Mr. Dukakis accepted the apology. It was a fine hour for both. It's impossible to live without ever having to say you're sorry. To do so is to take responsibility for your actions, to clean up what you've done. FREDERICK L. MUSANTE, JR.  Bridgeport, Conn., Aug. 6, 1992</p>
      </block>
